The data type "MM_Advisory" specifies information for travelers of itineraries and trip scheme including transfers. Unlike ISO 19133, all advisory information will be provided in character strings.

The code list "MM_AdvisoryCategory" lists the types of advisories used in Multimodal routing and navigation. Each value specifies an appropriate type of advisories to reach a destination point via potential waypoints using multimodal transportations.
The data type "MM_ModeConstraint" is used to specify mode preference by a traveler for the type of a mode.
The data type "MM_Constraint", a sub type of "NT_Constraint" from ISO19133, is an abstract class which is the root class of those types used to specify transfer and link restrictions.

The code list "MM_TransportationModeType" is the value domain for multimodal route segment categories. The list includes: "intracityBus", "intercityBus", "shuttleBust", "rovingBus", "subway", "lightrail", "tram", "railway", "highSpeedRailway", "ferry", "airway", "walk", "bike" and "taxi".
The data type "MM_ScheduleConstraint" specifies conditions for which the predefined schedule may have to be altered due to accidents, constructions and unscheduled events.
The data type "MN_WaitingTime" is used for describing cost arising from waiting time at transfer points along the multimodal route.
The type "MN_WeightedCost" is a cost function that is the sum of the numeric values of other cost functions with weights. MN_WeightedCost is a variant type of NS_WeightedCost in ISO 19133.
The data type "MN_TravelTime" is used for describing cost arising from line-haul travel time along the multimodal route.
The data type "MN_Time" is the root class for all types that have a time-valued cost.
The data type "MN_WeightedCostFunctionTerm" is a component of a cost function that is the sum of the numeric values of other cost functions with weights.
The data type "MN_WayPointsCost" is used for describing monetary cost related to waypoint activities such as shopping.
The data type "MN_CostElement" is the root of the collection of data types used to define cost functions. MN_CostElement is a variant type of NS_CostElement in ISO 19133.

The data type "MN_TotalCost" is used for describing monetary cost arising from total travel activities. For example, the total cost is composed of time, distance, out-of-pocket costs including parking fees, and cost related to waypoint activities such as shopping. Detailed explanation for MN_TotalCost can be found in Annex B.

The code list "MN_CostType" enumerated the types of cost function elements supported. The initial values of this list are "waitingTime", "travelTime", "totalCost", "fares", "wayPointsCost", "numberOfTransfers", and "distance.
The data type "MN_NumberOfTransfer" is the cost element used for counting modal transfers.
The data type "MN_ Distance" is the root class for all types that have a distance-valued cost.
The data type "MN_CostFunction" is a variant subtype of "NS_CostFunction" in ISO 19133.
The data type "MN_Fares" is used for describing monetary cost arising from out-of-pocket costs for travel.
The data type "MN_MonetaryCost" is the root class for all types that have a monetary-valued cost.
The data type "MN_ Counts" is the root class for all types that have a count-valued cost.
The data type "MN_RenderingResponse" contains rendered travel instructions corresponding to a multimodal route.
The data type "MN_RouteResponse" describes the route response for a multimodal navigation service.
The data type "MN_Itinerary" is a variant subtype of NS_InstructionList in ISO 19133. MN_Itinerary specifies an ordered list of traveling instructions on the multimodal transportation network.
The class "MN_CostedTransfer" is used to represent a transfer for which the cost has been calculated according to a given cost function.

The data type "MN_RouteRequest" is the itinerary request specifying the origin (starting point), waypoints, and destination (ending point) of the requested route. This data type is a variant sub type of "NS_RouteRequest" from ISO 19133.
The data type "MN_RenderingRequest" formats a request to translate a route into one or more forms usable in the navigation services.

The type "MM_NonFixedRouteSegment" is a route segment not operated based on a schedule. Route segments may be chosen by a traveler or by an operator of the mode on the route segment at their will. For example, the route segments by a taxi are likely to be defined by either the traveler or the taxi driver, but not by a predefined schedule.

The type "MM_Transfer" is used to represent a multimodal transfer that occurs at a transfer node of the multimodal transportation network. MM_Transfer specifies both which route segment enters the transfer node and which route segment exits the transfer node.

The type "MM_Network" is a type which aggregates MM_RouteSegment and MM_TransferNode. Since MM_RotueSegment is a sub type of NT_Network in ISO 19133, MM_Network holds a topological complex of dimension 1

The type "MM_RouteSegment" is used to delineate any route segments between two transfer nodes. Transfer nodes, such as bus stop, subway station, bus terminal and ferry terminal are where modal changes occur. The type "MM_RouteSegment" is a subtype of "NT_Network" in ISO 19133. The route segment may have two sub types: a fixed route segment such as transit route segment and a non-fixed route segment.

The code list "MM_TransferNodeType" is the value domain for the transfer nodes. The list includes: "bus stop", "taxi stop", "subway station", "lightrail station", "railway station", "intercity bus terminal", "platform", "gate", "port", "airport", "park-and-ride", "public parking lot", and "private parking lot".

The type "MM_TransferNode" is a topological node which has co-boundaries with potential route segments on the multimodal network. At a transfer node, a traveling mode changes or a transfer occurs. A transfer node is either a fixed point (e.g. bus stop, subway station, etc.) or an arbitrary point (e.g. any point on a road to take a taxi) on the base network.
The type "MM_FixedRouteSegment" describes a route segment of public transport modes which operate on predefined schedules.

The type "MM_Route" describes routes defined by a geometric object (a composite curve), and starts and stops positions on the geometry. MM_Route is the counterpart of NT_Route in ISO 19133. Therefore, the properties and the behaviors of MM_Route are the same except that MM_Route returns a sequence of route segments and MM_Route aggregates an ordered set of trip schemes.
The type "MM_TripScheme" is used to describe trip schemes for a traveler on the multimodal network. A trip scheme is a valid sequence of actions, given by a sequence of transfers.
The type "MM_ScheduleInfo" describes time schedules for a fixed route segment.

The data type "MM_RouteSummary" contains route summary information which is inherited from NT_RouteSummary in ISO 19133. MM_RouteSummary contains more attributes than NT_RouteSummary to provide appropriate multimodal routing services.
